
# Business Recommendations Report
## Smart City Complaint Analysis — Civic Data Analyst Findings

---

## 1. Key Findings

### 1.1 Complaint Volume & Categories
- 50,000 complaints analyzed across 8 zones and 7 categories.
- **Garbage Collection** (7,295) and **Public Safety** (7,291) are the two most frequent complaint categories, closely followed by Traffic Congestion (7,163) and Street Light Failure (7,126).
- **Water Supply** (6,963) is the least frequent category, but still a significant volume.
- Categories are fairly evenly distributed (no single category dominates), meaning the city needs **broad-based service improvement**, not a single-issue fix.

### 1.2 Geographic Hotspots
- **South-West Zone (6,443), Central Zone (6,417), and Industrial Zone (6,319)** are the top 3 complaint hotspots.
- The spread between the highest zone (South-West, 6,443) and the lowest (North-East, 6,071) is relatively narrow (~6%), indicating complaints are a **city-wide issue**, not isolated to one area.
- The Department vs Zone heatmap shows Police Dept in Central Zone (957) and South-West Zone (953) and Sanitation Dept in South Zone (957) and Industrial Zone (934) carry the heaviest localized loads.

### 1.3 Resolution Efficiency
- Overall **Resolution Rate is 64.95%** — roughly 1 in 3 complaints (17,527) remain Pending or In Progress.
- **Average resolution time is 8.11 days** across all categories — remarkably consistent (8.0–8.2 days) regardless of category, suggesting resolution speed is driven more by **process/staffing capacity** than by the nature of the complaint.
- **Priority system works correctly**: High priority complaints resolve in ~4.0 days vs. Low priority at ~12.5 days — a 3x difference. This confirms triage logic is functioning, but it also means low-priority issues linger for nearly two weeks on average.

### 1.4 Citizen Satisfaction
- Average satisfaction score is **2.75 / 5.0** — below the midpoint, indicating room for improvement.
- **Strong negative correlation (-0.71) between Resolution Delay and Satisfaction** — this is the single most actionable insight in the dataset. Every additional day of delay measurably reduces how citizens rate their resolution experience.
- This means **speed of resolution, not just eventual resolution, drives satisfaction**. A complaint resolved in 3 days vs 15 days produces a meaningfully different citizen experience even if both are eventually "Resolved."

