## 2. Business Questions — Answered

**1. Which complaint categories occur most frequently?**
Garbage Collection and Public Safety, followed closely by Traffic Congestion and Street Light Failure. All categories are within ~5% of each other — this is a multi-front problem.

**2. Which areas experience recurring civic problems?**
South-West, Central, and Industrial Zones consistently report the highest complaint volumes across nearly every category, based on the Zone vs Category matrix.

**3. Which departments take the longest to resolve complaints?**
Sanitation Dept has the highest average delay (8.21 days), though differences between departments are small. The bigger driver of delay is **Priority level**, not department.

**4. What factors reduce citizen satisfaction?**
Resolution delay is the dominant factor (correlation -0.71). Department and zone have only marginal influence on satisfaction compared to how long the complaint took to resolve.

**5. What actions should city authorities prioritize?**
See recommendations below.

---

## 3. Recommendations

1. **Reduce resolution time for Low and Medium priority complaints.** These currently take 7.5–12.5 days. Since delay is the strongest driver of dissatisfaction, even shaving 2-3 days off this tier would likely move the needle on the 2.75/5.0 satisfaction score more than any other intervention.

2. **Target the 17,527 unresolved complaints (35% of total) with a backlog clearance initiative.** A high pending/in-progress rate erodes trust regardless of eventual outcome.

3. **Focus staffing/resource reviews on South-West, Central, and Industrial Zones**, which consistently rank highest across categories — these may benefit from dedicated rapid-response units rather than city-wide-only resourcing.

4. **Investigate Electricity Dept's process** — it has the lowest resolution rate and satisfaction of all departments, even though the gap is small. A focused root-cause review (staffing, parts/inventory delays, escalation process) is warranted.

5. **Set an SLA (Service Level Agreement) explicitly tied to satisfaction targets**, e.g., "resolve 80% of Low priority complaints within 7 days" — since the data shows delay (not category or department) is what citizens actually feel.

6. **Use the Urgency Score (Priority x Delay composite)** introduced in this analysis to proactively flag complaints that are slipping through the cracks — high priority complaints that are also running long should trigger automatic escalation.

